<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>BIS Select Committee written evidence on the future of higher education</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Open University</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">(WSC022)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Executive Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Open University (OU)</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In responding to this inquiry, the OU draws on its longstanding research expertise in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gender and STEM issues, and its unique experience as a UK-wide university, employing a significant number of women STEM academics and researchers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Key research findings </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are unique pressures and demands on women who aspire to academic careers in STEM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> subjects. Many perceive that a STEM career will not fit with their aspirations for family life, meaning many choose to leave and do not return.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are less likely than men to put themselves forward for promotion and are less likely to embrace a strateg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ic approach to developing their careers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The lack of women at senior levels results in fewer role models to encourage women into the field. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Recommendations for Government Action</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Athena SWAN accreditation scheme is under strain because of increasing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">demand from HEIs. It should be adequately resourced to support the improvement of opportunities for women in STEM.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Higher Education Institutions (HEIs) to be required to engage in schemes such as Athena SWAN and Project JUNO.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Small-scale funding for specif</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ic projects can have a significant influence on the sector.  We would recommend provision of such funding to institutions to equip women to pursue long-term academic careers in STEM subjects.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">About The Open University</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Open University is the largest UK</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> university, with around 250,000 students and 1,100 academic /research staff. It is the only UK university operating in all four UK nations, giving it a unique UK-wide perspective on the issue of women academics in STEM subjects. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU attracts a high p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">roportion of female students. Our supported open learning model provides the flexibility for students to fit study around their other commitments including jobs, childcare or other caring responsibilities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">50.1% of OU academic and research staff are wome</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n, compared to 44% across the UK (ECU 2009-10 data).  The proportion of female STEM academic and research staff is </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lower (38%).  The OU recently gained an institutional Athena SWAN Bronze Award, and is taking forward an action plan to improve opportunities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for women to advance their academic STEM careers at the OU. We are preparing two Athena SWAN departmental submissions for this autumn.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU’s response to this inquiry draws both on our experience as an employer of women STEM academics and researchers, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and on our own research into gender and STEM issues undertaken by our Faculties of Mathematics, Computing &amp; Technology; Science; Education &amp; Language </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Studies; and the Institute of Educational Technology. It is also based on our knowledge of the field as le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ading gender and STEM researchers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU offers a range of career patterns for women academics that vary from the rest of the sector. An example is our regional academics, who are required to demonstrate excellence in teaching and management roles when a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pplying for promotion, rather than in research excellence.  We also provide good opportunities for women returning to part-time work as Associate Lecturers - a route highly valued by these staff (Donovan </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2005). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU has 30 years of expertise in gender and STEM research and practice. It was a founding partner in the UK Resources Centre for Women in SET (UKRC) and was a key partner with UKRC in delivering projects for women returners, including the OU’s specially</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> designed online course ‘Return to SET. Between 2005 and 2011 (when funding was withdrawn), this provided training and support for over 1000 women returning to STEM professions after a career break.  (Herman and Webster, 2010: Herman </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et al, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2011)</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ounded and continues to host the </span><a href="http://genderandset.open.ac.uk/index.php/genderandset"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Internation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">l Journal of Gender Science and Technology</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, an online open access journal that provides a voice for the research and practitioner community w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">orking on gender issues in STEM.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This submission references new research from this journal addressing the issues of concern to the Inquiry. Our knowledge of international research in this field makes us aware that the issue is complex and there are many di</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fferent ways of viewing the nature of the problem and potential solutions. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Numbers of women in all careers decline further up the career ladder, so reasons for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women’s lack of progression are similar to those in other occupations, especially in STEM careers outside academia. However, there are specific factors relating to academic career progression which contribute to the small numbers of women at the highest le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">vels of STEM academic careers. The Royal Society of Edinburgh’s report ‘Tapping all our Talents’ (2012) presents a comprehensive review and analysis of these issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.45pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a large body of research on women’s under-representation in STEM academic career</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s both in the UK and elsewhere. Ceci and Williams (2011) conclude there is no evidence that this is due to gender differences in ability or motivation, rather social and cultural factors provide explanations for lower numbers and for the decline further up</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the career ladder. While these issues have been well documented for the STEM academic sector, the lack of women in senior positions is even more pronounced in industry. An analysis of UK graduate destination data found that only </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">29% of women STEM graduate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s went on to work in STEM industries compared with 55% of their male counterparts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Kirkup </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2010). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The pathway to an academic research career typically starts with a PhD followed by a number of short-term research contracts prior to gaining a perman</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ent academic/research post. This period of job insecurity can be lengthy, often meaning that competition for gaining a permanent post coincides with women’s childbearing years. This is a point at which many women leave and fail to return to the sector. Res</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">earch by OU academics shows that whilst this may be for practical reasons during pregnancy or due to the demands of childcare, there is also a perception by these young </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">researchers that a research career in STEM will not fit with aspirations for a family l</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ife (Whitelegg </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2002). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The nature of STEM research, which emphasises working in research teams, and the requirement for special technical facilities and laboratories can mean that flexible working, job sharing, part-time roles and opportunities to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">work from home are less available, making it particularly difficult for women to combine their STEM academic career with motherhood. OU research has demonstrated that young STEM researchers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">perceive that those working part-time are not on a career-track so</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> will not receive career development opportunities (Whitelegg et al, 2002). For bench researchers in some disciplines, there is a long-hours culture in laboratory environments where it is usual to run experiments in the evenings and over weekends.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ace these dilemmas in many other professions and may take career breaks and/or work part-time with the intention of re-accelerating their careers at a later date. However, perhaps uniquely in STEM research careers, it is extremely difficult to recover from</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a break in research activity in rapidly developing fields and to continue to progress on a strong career track. Hence the ideal worker in academic STEM research continues to be perceived as having a full-time, uninterrupted career.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A key indicator of suc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cess and a pre-requisite for career progression in academic research is a track record of publication in peer reviewed journals. Even a short maternity break can affect this publication</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> record, as has been recognised by the Research Excellence Framework 20</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">14, with a reduction in the number of publications required from researchers who have taken maternity leave.  However, the perception that a break resulting in fewer research outputs will affect career progression still remains amongst young STEM researche</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rs.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women who are mothers or carers often desire more flexibility in their working pattern. Academic careers can offer more flexibility than industry equivalent professions, with the possibility of working around school terms and holiday periods, althou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gh this is less evident in STEM areas. However, particularly in the UK, motherhood is often seen as indicating less commitment even if women do the same work, whereas fatherhood can be seen as a marker of status and actually increases the number of hours a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cademic men are at work (Ceci and Williams, 2011). STEM academic mothers feel they have to work harder than their colleagues in non-STEM departments (Kmec, 2013). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women STEM academics and researchers often have partners in the same field. A study of US s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cientists (Schiebinger et al, 2008), where dual career hiring is practiced, found that 83% of female scientists in academic couples are partnered with another scientist, compared with 54% of male scientists. One-third of respondents to the study were part </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of an academic couple and 10% had been hired together.  Their main reason for declining a job was that their partner could not be employed in the same location.  In the UK, where dual career hiring is not practiced, the 2010 ASSET survey found that 42% of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women working in STEM had STEM-employed partners compared to 20% of men. When competition for STEM academic jobs is very strong, both partners are unlikely to gain their next contracts at the same UK establishment. Academic STEM careers also often expect i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nternational mobility. In couples where both partners have academic careers, women are more likely to follow their male partners than the reverse (Ackers, 2004).</span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women’s identities in STEM careers are more precarious than men’s. They face an in/visibility paradox where their identities as woman and scientist/engineer can be in conflict (Faulkner, 2007) </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#111111; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and they experience identity interference related to ‘workplace</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#111111; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> climate, perceptions of job </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#111111; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">opportunities, workload, research funding, resources/equipment, networking opportunities, professional recognition and respect, and work-family balance’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Steinke, 2013). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Academic careers may develop slowly and turnover of aca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">demic staff is also slow. For these reasons, culture change and gender parity could take years to achieve and there is a danger that demographic inertia will develop (Bakian and Sullivan, 2010). Proactive intervention is required.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women are less likely th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an men to put themselves forward for promotion perhaps because of a lack of confidence leading to a belief that competition will be too fierce to achieve success (Newsome, undated report). They may be more reluctant to embrace a strategic approach to devel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oping their careers, and for example may prioritise teaching and pastoral work over research, with a negative effect on long-term career prospects (Barrett and Barrett, 2011). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Both men and women can benefit from careers advice and encouragement from more</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> senior male/female colleagues. For women, in areas where there are currently no other women, this type of mentoring may not be available or encouraged.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientif</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">ically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The exit of women from junior academic research roles means fewer women available for senior positions and perpetuates the lack of role models for younger women studying STEM </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">subjects. Fewer women STEM academics also results in the culture remaining masculine so that a ‘chilly climate’ for women persists. This lack of role models also affects the number of undergraduate and school students choosing STEM subjects.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The OU follow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed up graduates of its ‘Return to SET’ course after five years, and found female STEM graduates had mostly returned to STEM jobs, but in different employment sectors and in particular into the health and education sectors. Many felt these careers offered m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ore flexibility but still enabled them to use their scientific skills, and offered the possibility of working from home or part-time in order to combine working with family life. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, moving into these fields usually entailed the trade-off of taking lo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wer paid and lower skilled jobs. Some went back into teaching roles within universities but on short-term contracts with no job security </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(Whitelegg </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">et al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2002; Herman, 2012).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The consequences of women failing to remain in or return to high level STEM pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fessions in general are a loss of skills and talent and a waste of national resource in an area which is predicted to underpin economic growth, particularly in physics-based areas (IOP, 2012).</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> retain women graduates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Athena SWAN and Project JUNO are effective mechanisms for identifying issues, highlighting good practice and obtaining institutional commitment to changes wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ich improve opportunities for women STEM academics. It is important that there are strong incentives for universities to participate in these schemes and resource them adequately. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Examples of good practice to support women include:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provide a period of de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dicated paid research time for those returning from maternity leave.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Hold meetings during core hours.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provide childcare on site.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fund childcare to enable attendance at conferences.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provide networks for students to meet women academics and develop career st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rategies (e.g. Interconnect).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provide career development advice and support (e.g. work by Vitae).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Provide mentoring and coaching opportunities for both early career researchers and women aspiring to senior roles.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ensure women have equal visibility in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">media.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ensure that there are women on conference panels or as keynote speakers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mentor women to take public appointment roles (Morton and Tobbell, 2011). </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? </span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Athena SWAN, which is supported by the Equality Challenge Unit, is under strain because of increasing demand for its accreditation from HEIs.  We consider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that it is a very effective agent for change, and that it should be adequately resourced to fulfil its role.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We would encourage the UK governments to require universities to engage with schemes such as Athena SWAN and Project JUNO in order to make a step</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> change in opportunities for women academics in STEM areas.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Small amounts of funding for specific projects frequently accelerate change by influencing the sector to follow best practice.   We believe that the UK governments can have a significant role in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">making available relatively small-scale funding, through their Funding Councils or other mechanisms, to institutions to equip women to pursue their careers over the long term, or to restart careers after a break, or a period of part-time working, for examp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">le:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Funding for women STEM returner schemes.   The OU online ‘Return to SET’ course was a very successful example. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Support and fund schemes that enable women academics to refresh their STEM skills after a career break (e.g. Daphne Jackson Fellowships).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nsure funding for dedicated research time on return from maternity leave.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:3pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ackers, L. (2004) Managing relationships in peripatetic careers: Scientific mobility in the European Union. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Women's Studies International Forum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 27</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(3), 189-201. doi: doi:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">10.1016/j.wsif.2004.03.001</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Athena Survey of Science, Engineering and Technology (ASSET) Survey (2010) Available at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">http://www.athenasurvey.org.uk/index.html</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Accessed 29 August 2013).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#111111; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bakian  A., </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; color:#111111; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and Sullivan